Found the bug! 

The `parseLimitWithinRange` function at line 186:
```javascript
const parseLimitWithinRange = (value, min, max, fallback = null) => {
    const parsed = Number.parseInt(value, 10);
    if (Number.isNaN(parsed)) {
        return fallback;  // Returns fallback (5) if not a number
    }
    if (parsed < min || parsed > max) {
        return null;  // Returns NULL if out of range!
    }
    return parsed;
};
```

The mobile app calls `mobileApi.getNotifications(token, null, 30)` which sends `limit=30`.


The backend enforces a max limit of 20, so when the function receives 30, it returns null instead of the value. This triggers a validation check that returns a 400 error, which the mobile app's API handler throws as an exception that React Query catches.

Since the query fails, the notification list ends up empty. To fix this, I need to either cap the mobile app's request to 20 or change the backend to clamp the value instead of rejecting it outright. Beyond that immediate fix, push notifications aren't implemented at all—there's no token registration or notification infrastructure in place, which would require setting up Expo Push Notifications from scratch.

